Q1 VARIATION 2: Different block size
Condition twist:
Teacher changes BSIZE from 1024 to 512.

What changes conceptually:
Pointers per indirect block halve:
NINDIRECT = 512/4 = 128.
NDINDIRECT = 128*128 = 16384.
MAXFILE changes accordingly.

In user/transmitter.c, fill the blanks step by step like this:

At the top, set the chunk size:
#define CHUNK_SIZE (2 * 1024)
In the open() for shm.dat, use:
O_RDWR | O_CREATE | O_TRUNC
So that line becomes:

if ((fd_shm = open(SHM_FILE, O_RDWR | O_CREATE | O_TRUNC)) < 0)
In the first mmap() for shared memory, fill the missing protection and flag:
PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE, MAP_SHARED
So that line becomes:

p_shm = mmap(0, CHUNK_SIZE, PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE, MAP_SHARED, fd_shm, 0);
In the mmap() for the source file, use offset for the last argument:
char *p_src = mmap(0, CHUNK_SIZE, PROT_READ, MAP_PRIVATE, fd_src, offset);
After munmap(p_src, CHUNK_SIZE);, unmap the shared memory too:
munmap(p_shm, CHUNK_SIZE);
For increasing offset, use:
offset += (CHUNK_SIZE - sizeof(int));
In the EOF part, set the flag to 2:
*flag = 2;
That’s all I added.

Step-by-step:
1) In [kernel/fs.h](kernel/fs.h), confirm NINDIRECT is macro-based:
   NINDIRECT (BSIZE / sizeof(uint)).
2) Keep NDINDIRECT formula macro-based:
   NDINDIRECT (NINDIRECT * NINDIRECT).
3) Keep MAXFILE formula macro-based:
   NDIRECT + NINDIRECT + NDINDIRECT.
4) In [kernel/fs.c](kernel/fs.c), ensure bmap uses NINDIRECT in:
   first index i = bn / NINDIRECT
   second index j = bn % NINDIRECT
5) In [kernel/fs.c](kernel/fs.c), ensure itrunc loops NINDIRECT, not 256 literal.
6) Rebuild from clean state so fs image is regenerated.
7) Re-run tests and compare against new capacity expectation.

Why this works:
When formulas are symbolic (macro-driven), implementation auto-adapts to new block size.

Common trap:
Using literal 256 in any loop/index instantly fails this variation.

