Q1 VARIATION 3: Sparse-file correctness check
Condition twist:
Teacher adds a sparse-file test.
Requirement: reads from holes should return zeros, and read path must not allocate blocks.

What changes conceptually:
Current xv6 read path calling bmap can accidentally allocate blocks.
Need split mapping into:
- lookup-only for read
- allocate-on-demand for write

Step-by-step:
1) In [kernel/fs.c](kernel/fs.c), add helper bmap_lookup(ip, bn):
   same navigation logic as bmap, but never calls balloc.
   returns 0 if mapping missing.
2) Keep existing bmap as allocate-on-demand for writes.
3) In readi, replace bmap call with bmap_lookup.
4) If bmap_lookup returns 0:
   synthesize zeros for that chunk into destination buffer.
5) In writei, keep using allocating bmap.
6) Keep itrunc unchanged except it should naturally free only allocated blocks.
7) Test:
   create sparse region using lseek-style equivalent pattern (or custom user test),
   read hole, verify bytes are zero,
   verify disk blocks did not grow from reads.

Why this works:
Sparse semantics require non-allocating reads.
Only writes should allocate physical blocks.

Common trap:
Using normal bmap in read path silently allocates and fails sparse test.

