Q2 VARIATION 2: Relative symlink targets
Condition twist:
Symlink target may be relative path, and must resolve relative to directory containing the symlink, not current working directory.

What changes conceptually:
Need path normalization when target does not start with slash.

Step-by-step:
1) In [kernel/sysfile.c](kernel/sysfile.c), when reading symlink target:
   if target starts with slash, treat as absolute (existing behavior).
2) If target is relative:
   compute base directory of currently opened symlink path.
3) Build combined path:
   combined = dirname(current_link_path) + "/" + target.
4) Normalize simple dot segments:
   handle "." and ".." if required by test.
5) Resolve combined path via namei.
6) Continue loop for chained links.
7) Keep depth guard and lock release sequence unchanged.
8) Add tests:
   /a/b/link -> "../x/file"
   should resolve to /a/x/file.

Why this works:
Real symlink semantics are path-based and context-sensitive.
Relative target must be interpreted from link location.

Common trap:
Resolving relative target from process cwd instead of symlink’s parent dir.

